          desc: "The deadliest pandemic in human history that killed one-third to half of Europe's population.",
          content: "<p class=\"mb-4\">The Black Death was caused by <strong>Yersinia pestis</strong> bacteria carried by rat fleas. First reported in China in the 1330s, it spread westward via trade routes.</p><p class=\"mb-4\">The plague reached Europe through Sicilian ports in October 1347. Within 3 years it spread from the Mediterranean to Scandinavia.</p><p class=\"mb-4\">Estimated death toll: <strong>75–200 million worldwide</strong>. Europe lost 30–60% of its population. European population did not recover until around 1500.</p><p class=\"mb-4\">The massive labor shortage weakened feudalism. The Catholic Church lost authority by failing to stop the plague.</p><p class=\"mb-4\">Quarantine was first practiced in Ragusa (Dubrovnik) in 1377 — a system still used during COVID-19. The Black Death became the foundation of modern epidemiology.</p>",
